title: For Sale/Trade:  HK 556A1 mint condition
postcontent:
This is the rolls-Royce of A.R. 15's nothing touches it.  I build them so I know anyone who tells you this is overpriced has either not had the privilege to fire one or can't afford one.  
The MR556A1 uses the HK proprietary gas piston operating system, employing a piston and a solid operating “pusher” rod in place of the gas tube normally found in AR15/M16/M4-style firearms.
This method of operation virtually eliminates malfunctions that are common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. This is the same key feature critical to the success of the HK416 rifles used by leading military and law enforcement customers.

title: For Sale:  1918 (SMLE) LEE-ENFIELD NO. 1 MK III* .303 BRITISH CALIBER SPORTERIZED BOLT ACTION RIFLE
postcontent: This is a 1918 vintage (SMLE) Lee-Enfield No. 1 MK III* .303 British caliber sporterized bolt action rifle which has had the stock cut down to improve the weight of the gun for hunting and carrying the weapon. It has the stock 25" barrel and the original adjustable rear sight with the original front sight still attached. This is a 10-shot detachable magazine stripper clip fed weapon with a fixed stripper clip bridge over the receiver which is different than the earlier guns in the series which were two piece with one half attached to the bolt. It was built in 1918 at the Enfield RSAF (Royal Small Arms Factory) in the London Burough of Enfield in England. The top of the barrel has the B.S.A. Co logo stamping of the 3 standing rifles with the outline pattern. The fit/finish of the rifle is in good shape with the stock being in very good condition at this point after being shortened. I have not fired this particular weapon since I purchased it about 10 years ago but all parts seem to be functional at this point. I am looking to sell this rifle for a cash offer and I am not looking to make any trades at this point.

title: For Sale:  Colt Model 1862 Police .36 Pistol / Hand guns For Sale
postcontent:
TEXT OR CALL: REDACTED Colt Model 1862 Police .36 Percussion Revolver

Ever since Colt marketed pocket revolvers, their handy size has proved to be very popular for self defense and, whilst it is valid to say that the Colt 1862 Model Police revolver was meant for those individuals engaged in a security role, its attributes made it equally desirable for the outlaw alike. Consequently, as this was to be Colt's last offering of a cap and ball pistol before their arms production went over completely to metallic cartridges, the model 1862 Police has always been in short supply.

Even when metallic cartridges were first available, not everyone could access them, preferring to make their own balls and continue muzzle loading.

In this transitional period, Colt realised that the metallic cartridge was the way forward so only 30% of the components produced for the 1862 Police revolver were ever assembled into cap and ball pistols. The majority of the barrels, cylinders and frames were instead utilised in the production of their equally popular pocket rimfire revolvers. With that, Colt's percussion era drew to a close and today, this Police revolver has become a rare pistol for collectors to find.

Presented in very good and crisp condition, this Colt 1862 Police revolver is a superb looking piece for the collector - totally original with matching serial numbers throughout. The action is also working very well, with smooth operation and indexing of the cylinder as well as tight lock up and strong mainspring. The bore and chambers are all in good order too with clearly stamped address and patent dates.

TEXT OR CALL: REDACTED

postcontent:
TEXT OR CALL: REDACTED
Presentation Grade .442 Webley No.1 Gate Loading Revolver

This is a superior presentation grade No.1 gate loading revolver, made by Webley c.1868. This would have been made to special order, all hand engraved at their factory and then nickel plated and finish off with the ivory grips before being retailed by T. Miller of Sunderland and marked on the top strap. No doubt this would have been made for a well heeled gentleman, possibly serving as his personal protection revolver, quite likely accompanying him on travels overseas, where the smooth cool grips and protective finish would have been an asset in a hot climate.

This type of Webley revolver seldom comes to the market and in this condition, it would prove to be a fine addition to a collection. Fully working with positive lock up and good spring action, the revolver retains much of its original finish. The bore and chambers are all in good condition throughout. Only the grip has an old well executed period repair to the right side.

title: For Sale:  Old Thompson Center Scout muzzleloader
postcontent: Up for sale is my old TC Scout.  If I remember correctly from my research when I first bought it a few years ago, it is from 1984 or so.  It looks like a bush gun or old 30/30 without the lever action.  Uses the old primer caps (11s I think).  Solid wood (maple I believe) stock and foregrip.  Heavy duty, well build weapon.  Works fine.  Used it up until last year and have gotten a few nice deer with it.  I just purchased a newer, more modern ML this past season that just ended so I just have no need for this one. Does come with the leather strap. No scope. Images are sample photos from internet, but look just like it.  Normal scuffs and such for a weapon of that age. Would make a great first ML for someone who wants to see if they like black powder hunting and doesn't want to spend a lot of money, or for someone who just likes the older and more classic muzzle loaders than the ones today.  Disclaimer: although it fires fine and accurate, I cannot get the nipple off to replace it.  It has been this way since I bought it a few years ago.  Still fires fine, but it could use a replacement eventually.  From what I could find, the Scout had a nipple wrench specific to that make and I never got one.  I'm sure a gunsmith or a person with more experience than me with them will have no issues getting it off and/or replaced.  Will take $60.00 cash or 3 troy ounces of silver as payment. Less than half of what most people are asking for these. Prefer texts, but will also answer emails as I see them.  Will also include some caps, bore butter, and some ball ammo and some TC mini or maxi ball bullets to get you started.  The included accessories come to almost as much as I am asking for the gun.  Thank you for looking. (574)377-six three one four.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1942 Mosin Nagant w/ Nikon Monarch scope and many upgrades
postcontent:
This 1942 Izhevsk 91/30 Mosin Nagant rifle was hand selected from an entire crate of cosmoline-coated Nagants because of its exceptional rifling and construction.  I had my gunsmith cut 6 inches off of the barrel and give it a new recessed crown (pictured).  I removed the wooden stock and replaced it with the black Arch Angel stock with adjustable cheek piece, buttpad, and detachable magazine.  I bedded the front lug and back of the stock with Acraglass bedding compound.  A low-profile steel Jmeck scope mount was installed, and the stock had to be fitted to accommodate this mount - then I partially bedded the area to assure a rock-solid fit.  I sent my bolt off to Max Shepherd for a custom bolt job with a satin finish.  The drop-in trigger system by Timney was installed, which GREATLY improved the rifles performance, as well as adding the top thumb safety lever.  Burris XTR 1-inch low scope rings were added, to firmly secure the Nikon Monarch Mildot 2.5-10x42 riflescope w/ sunshade (scope alone is worth $375).  No lapping was needed when scope was mounted, and all screws were torqued to spec with a torque limiting wrench system and BLUE loctite.  I also added a front screw for a bipod.  Czech surplus ammunition rendered the best results from this weapon system, creating 3-round cloverleafs at 100yrds (1/2 inch groups).  However, I have NOT tried any 7.62x54R MATCH ammo or handloads in this rifle..  so who knows how accurate this system can truly become.  I just wanted to create a powerful tactical rifle that I could afford to shoot all day with hardly any worry about ammo costs.  The Archangel magazine provided with the stock does not function well (as is the story with almost all of the early runs of this stock).  There is a fix on youtube that involves baking the magazine in the oven but I have not attempted this or bought one of the new magazines - I simply loaded single rounds from the bench.  I will NOT part-out this rifle and its accessories, so don't ask.  Price $450 for the entire system.

WILL TRADE for an AK47 and/or AK Variant, even a WASR if it's a nice one.  Must be 7.62x39.  No SKS rifles.
